[[ja:霧島六社権現]] [[sn:Kirishima Rokusha Gongen]] [[en:Kirishima Rokusha Gongen]]

'''Kirishima Rokusha Gongen''' (霧島六社権現) refers to a collective of six {{ill|Shinto shrines|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located around {{ill|Mount Kirishima|ja|霧島山|qq=draft}}, straddling the border between {{ill|Miyazaki Prefecture|ja|宮崎県|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|ja|鹿児島県|qq=draft}}. It is also known as '''Kirishima Rokusho Gongen''' (霧島六所権現).
* {{ill|Kirishima Mine Shrine|ja|霧島岑神社|qq=draft}} (Kirishima Mine Central Rokusho Gongen; affiliated temple: Setaoji) – Located in {{ill|Kobayashi, Miyazaki|ja|小林市|qq=draft}}, formerly a prefectural shrine. * '''Ebisumori Shrine''' (Ebisumori Rokusho Gongen; affiliated temple: {{ill|Hōkō-in (Kobayashi)|ja|宝光院|qq=draft}}) – Also in Kobayashi, Miyazaki; merged with Kirishima Mine Shrine during the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|qq=draft}}. * {{ill|Sano Shrine|ja|狭野神社|qq=draft}} (Sano Gongen; affiliated temple: Jintoku-in) – Located in {{ill|Takaharu, Miyazaki|ja|高原町|qq=draft}}, formerly a prefectural shrine. Designated as a branch shrine of {{ill|Miyazaki Jingū|ja|宮崎神宮|qq=draft}} in 1915, later regaining independence and listed as a special shrine under the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|ja|神社本庁|qq=draft}} in 1976. * Higashi Kirishima Shrine (Higashi Kirishima Gongen; affiliated temple: Chokushō-in) – Located in {{ill|Miyakonojo, Miyazaki|ja|都城市|qq=draft}}, formerly a prefectural shrine. * Kirishima Higashi Shrine (Kirishima Higashi Gozaisho Gongen; affiliated temple: Shakujō-in) – Located in Takaharu, Miyazaki; formerly a village shrine. * {{ill|Kirishima Shrine|ja|霧島神宮|qq=draft}} (Kirishima Nishi Gozaisho Gongen; affiliated temple: Karin-ji) – Located in {{ill|Kirishima, Kagoshima|ja|霧島市|qq=draft}}, formerly an imperial shrine.
The Kirishima Rokusha Gongen was organized by the monk {{ill|Shōkū|ja|性空|qq=draft}}, who practiced {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft}} during the reign of {{ill|Emperor Murakami|ja|村上天皇|qq=draft}}. Although these shrines currently enshrine deities from Japanese mythology, particularly the {{ill|Three Generations of Hyuga|ja|日向三代|qq=draft}}, their origins lie in ancient {{ill|mountain worship|ja|山岳信仰|qq=draft}}, with Mount Kirishima itself revered as sacred. The area served as a center for Shugendō practitioners.
In addition to the six shrines listed above, some sources include {{ill|Shiratori Shrine (Ebino)|ja|白鳥神社 (えびの市)|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ebino, Miyazaki|ja|えびの市|qq=draft}}. The ''{{ill|Sangoku Meishō Zue|ja|三国名勝図会|qq=draft}}'' mentions '''Hanamai Rokusho Gongen''' in {{ill|Miyakonojo|ja|都城市|qq=draft}} and '''Yasuhara Kirishima Daigongen (Naka Kirishima Gongen)''' as part of the Kirishima Rokusha Gongen. This suggests that the grouping may have varied over time, reflecting the prominence of different shrines around Mount Kirishima<ref>Akihiko Kuroiwa, "Kirishima Rokusho Gongen" in ''Miyazaki Prefecture Shrine Records,'' Miyazaki Prefectural Shrine Office, 1988.</ref>.
