'''Kirishima Rokusha Gongen''' (霧島六社権現) refers to a collective of six [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrines]] located around [[:en:Mount Kirishima|Mount Kirishima]], straddling the border between [[:en:Miyazaki Prefecture|Miyazaki Prefecture]] and [[:en:Kagoshima Prefecture|Kagoshima Prefecture]]. It is also known as '''Kirishima Rokusho Gongen''' (霧島六所権現).
* {{ill|Kirishima Mine Shrine|ja|霧島岑神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kirishima Mine Shrine|qq=}} (Kirishima Mine Central Rokusho Gongen; affiliated temple: Setaoji) – Located in [[:en:Kobayashi, Miyazaki|Kobayashi, Miyazaki]], formerly a prefectural shrine. * '''Ebisumori Shrine''' (Ebisumori Rokusho Gongen; affiliated temple: {{ill|Hōkō-in (Kobayashi)|ja|宝光院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōkō-in (Kobayashi)|qq=}}) – Also in Kobayashi, Miyazaki; merged with Kirishima Mine Shrine during the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]]. * {{ill|Sano Shrine|ja|狭野神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sano Shrine|qq=}} (Sano Gongen; affiliated temple: Jintoku-in) – Located in [[:en:Takaharu, Miyazaki|Takaharu, Miyazaki]], formerly a prefectural shrine. Designated as a branch shrine of [[:en:Miyazaki Jingū|Miyazaki Jingū]] in 1915, later regaining independence and listed as a special shrine under the [[:en:Association of Shinto Shrines|Association of Shinto Shrines]] in 1976. * Higashi Kirishima Shrine (Higashi Kirishima Gongen; affiliated temple: Chokushō-in) – Located in [[:en:Miyakonojō|Miyakonojo, Miyazaki]], formerly a prefectural shrine. * Kirishima Higashi Shrine (Kirishima Higashi Gozaisho Gongen; affiliated temple: Shakujō-in) – Located in Takaharu, Miyazaki; formerly a village shrine. * [[:en:Kirishima Shrine|Kirishima Shrine]] (Kirishima Nishi Gozaisho Gongen; affiliated temple: Karin-ji) – Located in [[:en:Kirishima, Kagoshima|Kirishima, Kagoshima]], formerly an imperial shrine.
The Kirishima Rokusha Gongen was organized by the monk {{ill|Shōkū|ja|性空|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkū|qq=}}, who practiced [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendō]] during the reign of [[:en:Emperor Murakami|Emperor Murakami]]. Although these shrines currently enshrine deities from Japanese mythology, particularly the {{ill|Three Generations of Hyuga|ja|日向三代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Three Generations of Hyuga|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, their origins lie in ancient [[:en:Mountain worship|mountain worship]], with Mount Kirishima itself revered as sacred. The area served as a center for Shugendō practitioners.
In addition to the six shrines listed above, some sources include {{ill|Shiratori Shrine (Ebino)|ja|白鳥神社 (えびの市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiratori Shrine (Ebino)|qq=}} in [[:en:Ebino, Miyazaki|Ebino, Miyazaki]]. The ''{{ill|Sangoku Meishō Zue|ja|三国名勝図会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangoku Meishō Zue|qq=}}'' mentions '''Hanamai Rokusho Gongen''' in [[:en:Miyakonojō|Miyakonojo]] and '''Yasuhara Kirishima Daigongen (Naka Kirishima Gongen)''' as part of the Kirishima Rokusha Gongen. This suggests that the grouping may have varied over time, reflecting the prominence of different shrines around Mount Kirishima<ref>Akihiko Kuroiwa, "Kirishima Rokusho Gongen" in ''Miyazaki Prefecture Shrine Records,'' Miyazaki Prefectural Shrine Office, 1988.</ref>.
